---
import ClerriLayout from '../../layouts/ClerriLayout.astro';
---
<ClerriLayout title="Paid Search Strategy" section="paid-search">

<div class="page-head">
  <div class="page-eyebrow">Channels & Budget · Paid Search Strategy</div>
  <h1 class="page-title">Fix it or own it — <em>the paid-search reset.</em></h1>
  <p class="page-sub">Built from 15 months of the actual Google Ads account. The diagnosis, the keyword reframe (you're fishing the wrong pond), a segmented SMB / Mid / DSO strategy, competitor conquest gaps, hard 90-day goals, and the Opascope meeting kit.</p>
</div>

<div class="page-body">

  <div class="takeaway">
    <span class="tk-lbl">Bottom line</span>
    <p>The account-wide data (corrected from a fuller export): you spend <strong>~$11.5K/mo, all Search</strong>, and <strong>~39% goes to bidding your own brand name</strong> while the Competitor, Fee-For-Service, Software, and Insurance-Alternatives campaigns sit <strong>paused</strong>. Real non-brand demand-gen runs ~$585/lead; only ~25 conversions/mo total; the account is littered with 50+ dead campaigns and widespread disapproved ads; conversion "value" is an assigned proxy (fake ROAS). <strong>You don't need more budget — you need to reallocate the $11.5K you have</strong> (cut brand, turn on conquest + problem-aware), prove a better CPL, then scale.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="progress-track"><div class="progress-fill" data-progress-fill="paid-search"></div></div>
  <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.75rem;color:var(--muted)">Actions taken: <span data-progress-here="paid-search">0 / 0</span></p>

  <h2>1 · Current state — the diagnosis</h2>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
  <table class="ptable">
    <thead><tr><th>Signal</th><th>What the data shows</th><th>Read</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td>Spend</td><td>~$11.5K/mo (last 30 days), 100% Search</td><td>Display built but entirely paused. The real account-wide figure (an earlier partial export showed only ~$3,200).</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Brand spend</strong></td><td><strong>~39% ($4,487)</strong> on Brand-Main/Kleer/mCPC</td><td><strong>Harvesting your own name</strong> — converts cheap, inflates the blended number. Brand-Main on Target Impression Share = vanity.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Conversions</td><td>25/mo total; ~12 non-brand</td><td>Thin for $11.5K. Blended CPL $460, but non-brand demand-gen is ~$585.</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Paused campaigns</strong></td><td>Competitor, Fee-For-Service, Software, Insurance-Alternatives all OFF</td><td><strong>Backwards</strong> — conquest + problem-aware campaigns are dark while brand eats 39%.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Account hygiene</td><td>60+ campaigns, ~54 paused/ended; "ads disapproved" widespread</td><td>A graveyard of past agencies. Memberships campaign: "search volume limited," opt-score 44/100.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Conversion value</td><td>Assigned proxy (~$960-1,350/conv)</td><td>Not real revenue → any ROAS reported is fictional. Confirm the 25 are real demo requests.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>Wasted spend</td><td>Consumer-insurance queries (Delta/Humana/MetLife portals) in search terms</td><td>Wrong audience — patients, not practices. Loose match types.</td></tr>
      <tr><td>CTR</td><td>Healthy on exact match</td><td>Top-of-funnel works; conversion + allocation is the break</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>

  <h2>2 · The reframe — <em>you're fishing the wrong pond.</em></h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:72ch">Every keyword in the account is <strong>solution-aware</strong> — someone already searching "dental membership plans." That catches two groups: researchers (not ready to buy) and DIY-ers (about to build their own — your real competitor). It misses the practice that hasn't connected its pain to "membership" yet. New SMB acquisition starts one step upstream.</p>
  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="card"><span class="pill pill-mint">Problem-aware</span><h4 style="margin:0.4rem 0">MISSING entirely</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">"dropping delta dental," "fee for service transition," "declining dental reimbursement," "increase practice revenue." The biggest new-SMB pool — and you bid on none of it.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><span class="pill pill-zest">Solution-aware</span><h4 style="margin:0.4rem 0">Over-indexed</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">"dental membership plans," "in house dental plans." Where 100% of budget sits. Fine, but crowded with researchers + DIY-ers.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><span class="pill pill-wine">Vendor-aware</span><h4 style="margin:0.4rem 0">STARVED</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">"dental membership software/platform" — your best CTR (14.5%), buyers seeking a vendor — got ~$1.1K total. Underfunded.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>3 · Segment strategy <em>(SMB / Mid / DSO).</em></h2>
  <div class="callout wine">
    <div class="lbl">Strategic honesty — say this in the meeting</div>
    <p style="margin:0"><strong>Paid search is an SMB + mid-market channel. It is NOT a DSO channel.</strong> DSO buying is committee-driven, low-volume, and happens via ABM + events + Becker's/GDN — not Google searches. Don't burn paid-search budget chasing DSOs; a handful of high-intent enterprise terms at most. Pushing search to "win DSOs" is how money disappears.</p>
  </div>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
  <table class="ptable">
    <thead><tr><th>Segment</th><th>Search role</th><th>Keyword focus</th><th>Conversion</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>SMB</strong> (1-9 loc)</td><td><strong>Primary engine</strong> — high volume, lower CPC, fast cycle</td><td>Problem-aware + solution-aware + in-house conquest</td><td>Demo request + calculator</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Mid / emerging groups</strong></td><td>Secondary — more sophisticated buyers</td><td>Software/platform terms, multi-location, competitor comparisons</td><td>Demo + ROI content</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>DSO / Enterprise</strong></td><td><strong>Minimal</strong> — defend a few high-intent terms only; rest is ABM/events</td><td>"enterprise dental membership software," brand defense</td><td>Hand to ABM, don't scale search</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>

  <h2>4 · The keyword architecture <em>(what to actually build).</em></h2>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Problem-aware (SMB) — NEW</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;line-height:1.55;padding-left:1.1rem;margin:0">
        <li>dropping delta dental / dropping ppo dentist</li>
        <li>fee for service transition dental practice</li>
        <li>declining dental insurance reimbursement</li>
        <li>how to reduce insurance dependence dental</li>
        <li>increase dental practice revenue / profitability</li>
        <li>dental patient retention strategies</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--clerri-green);margin-top:0.4rem">Upstream demand capture, ZERO paid competition, PEAK intent now (Delta class-actions May 2026; #1 dentist concern 2026 per ADA). The single best open lane.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Vendor-aware — FUND THESE</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;line-height:1.55;padding-left:1.1rem;margin:0">
        <li>dental membership software / platform</li>
        <li>membership plan software for dentists</li>
        <li>dental membership management software</li>
        <li>recurring revenue software dental practice</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--clerri-green);margin-top:0.4rem">Highest intent + best CTR, currently starved. Send to demo/product LPs.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Solution-aware — KEEP, refine</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;line-height:1.55;padding-left:1.1rem;margin:0">
        <li>dental membership plans (current core)</li>
        <li>in house / in office dental plans (conquest — DIY-ers)</li>
        <li>recurring revenue dental practice</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--clerri-green);margin-top:0.4rem">The "in-house" terms = your real competitor. Smart — but fix the conversion path.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="card">
      <h4>Conquest + brand defense</h4>
      <ul style="font-size:0.875rem;line-height:1.55;padding-left:1.1rem;margin:0">
        <li><strong>boomcloud alternative / pricing</strong> (highest priority)</li>
        <li>dentalhq pricing / alternative</li>
        <li><strong>Defend:</strong> clerri, kleer, membersy (Plan Forward bids "Clerri alternatives")</li>
        <li>Skip Subscribili (near-zero demand); negative "Pearl Dental" before any "Pearly" bid</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.72rem;color:var(--clerri-green);margin-top:0.4rem">Cheap, high-intent switchers. Pair with the "alternatives" comparison pages.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>5 · Competitor gaps <em>(researched, June 2026).</em></h2>
  <p class="mono muted" style="font-size:0.78rem">Positioning + conquest-page facts are verified from live competitor sites; volume/CPC is directional (no Ahrefs/SEMrush) — buy one month of Keyword Planner before committing budget.</p>
  <div style="overflow-x:auto">
  <table class="ptable">
    <thead><tr><th>Competitor</th><th>How they position (live H1)</th><th>Conquest pool</th><th>The play</th></tr></thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>BoomCloud</strong></td><td>"Dental Membership Software for In-Office Plans"</td><td><strong>Highest</strong> — flat $399/mo + migration friction</td><td>Paid "boomcloud alternative / pricing" — you already win organically, so paid = full SERP lockout</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>DentalHQ</strong></td><td>"Dental Membership Plan Platform" (pricing-led)</td><td>Moderate (price-driven)</td><td>Conquest on "dentalhq pricing"; counter with value, not price</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Plan Forward</strong></td><td>"Dental Membership Software for Private Practice"</td><td>Low — <strong>but they publish "Clerri Alternatives"</strong></td><td>DEFEND your brand SERP — they're already bidding to intercept your migrating customers</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Pearly</strong></td><td>"Dental Patient Billing Automation Software"</td><td>Off-target</td><td>⚠️ "Pearly" collides with "Pearl Dental" (AI imaging) — negative-keyword before any branded bid</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Subscribili</strong></td><td>"Platform powering the patient journey"</td><td><strong>Near-zero</strong> (verified null demand)</td><td>Cheap to own but thin — don't prioritize</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:0.92rem;line-height:1.6;max-width:74ch"><strong>The structural gaps (open lanes):</strong></p>
  <ul style="font-size:0.92rem;line-height:1.6;max-width:74ch">
    <li><strong>Problem-aware paid is wide open</strong> — NO competitor runs <em>paid</em> search on "drop Delta / drop PPO / fee for service." All competition there is organic. Biggest first-mover lane, and peak intent now (Delta lawsuits, May 2026).</li>
    <li><strong>DSO/multi-location vendor terms are thin</strong> — "dental membership software for DSOs / multi-location" is mostly Clerri-organic. Your "7 of top 10 DSOs" claim is a paid wedge nobody else can match.</li>
    <li><strong>The compliance niche is unguarded</strong> — "DMPO," "TPA license," "dental membership compliance 50 states" — only Subscribili touches it; near-zero paid competition, high-trust intent.</li>
    <li><strong>SEO conquest is live, paid conquest is the gap</strong> — clerri.com already ranks for "boomcloud-vs-clerri," "dentalhq-pricing," "best-boomcloud-alternatives." Paid layered on top locks the full result page.</li>
  </ul>
  <div class="callout zest-hi">
    <div class="lbl">Top 5 keyword plays — walk in with these</div>
    <ol style="margin:0;padding-left:1.2rem;font-size:0.95rem;line-height:1.6">
      <li><strong>Paid conquest: "boomcloud alternative / pricing"</strong> — highest switching intent; pair with the comparison pages you already rank for.</li>
      <li><strong>Problem-aware exact match: "drop delta dental," "drop ppo dental," "fee for service transition"</strong> — zero paid competition, peak intent. Land on a "leave insurance → membership" page.</li>
      <li><strong>"dental membership software for DSOs / multi-location"</strong> — defend your true differentiator where rivals are weak.</li>
      <li><strong>Compliance wedge: "dental membership compliance / DMPO / TPA 50 states"</strong> — cheap, high-trust, only Subscribili contests.</li>
      <li><strong>Brand defense: "clerri / kleer / membersy" (+ alternative / login / pricing)</strong> — protect the merged-brand SERP during the transition; Plan Forward is already bidding "Clerri alternatives."</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
  <p class="mono muted" style="font-size:0.78rem">Caveats for the room: validate the BoomCloud-2.0-migration angle with sales (couldn't confirm publicly); negative-keyword "Pearl Dental Software" before any "Pearly" bid; pull one month of Keyword Planner/Ahrefs before locking budget. Sources: live competitor sites + ADA News (Delta class-actions, May 2026).</p>

  <h2>6 · Kill the waste — <em>negative keywords, week 1.</em></h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:72ch">You're paying for <em>patients</em> looking for their own insurance. Add these as negatives immediately:</p>
  <p class="mono" style="font-size:0.82rem;background:var(--cotton-plus);padding:0.7rem 0.9rem;border-radius:0.5rem;line-height:1.7">delta dental · humana · metlife · cigna · aetna · mydelta · dentalquest · truassure · carefreedental · "ncd" · ".com" (portal-login intent) · "for business" / "for companies" / "for employees" (group benefits) · "california" + carrier terms · "full coverage" · "no annual maximum"</p>

  <h2>7 · Hard goals — <em>90 days.</em></h2>
  <div class="grid-3">
    <div class="card"><div class="rnum">&lt;$300</div><div class="rlbl">SMB demo CPL (from ~$600) via problem-aware + high-intent focus + waste removal + LP fix</div></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="rnum">3x</div><div class="rlbl">conversion volume (~5 → ~15/mo) at same or lower spend</div></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="rnum">20%+</div><div class="rlbl">of budget on high-intent vendor + conquest terms (from near-zero)</div></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="rnum">50+</div><div class="rlbl">negative keywords added to kill consumer-insurance waste</div></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="rnum">Wk 1</div><div class="rlbl">audit the conversion action + landing pages (healthy clicks, weak conversion = LP problem)</div></div>
    <div class="card"><div class="rnum">1</div><div class="rlbl">clear hard conversion defined (demo request) — stop counting soft actions</div></div>
  </div>

  <h2>8 · Fix or own it — <em>the in-house plan.</em></h2>
  <p style="color:var(--ink-soft);max-width:72ch">At ~$3,200/mo of media, this is very in-houseable — Google Ads at this scale isn't hard, and you'd reclaim the entire retainer. LogicalPosition-style management runs ~10% of spend (~$300-500/mo) vs. a $4.5-10K retainer. The build:</p>
  <div class="grid-2">
    <div class="card"><h4>Account structure</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">3 campaign clusters: (1) Problem-aware SMB → education/calculator LPs; (2) Solution + vendor-aware → demo/product LPs; (3) Conquest + brand-defense → comparison LPs. One hard conversion: demo request.</p></div>
    <div class="card"><h4>Landing pages by intent</h4><p style="font-size:0.875rem">Problem-aware → "is membership right for you?" + calculator. Vendor-aware → product/demo. Conquest → "[competitor] alternative" comparison. The CTRs are healthy; the LP is likely the conversion bottleneck.</p></div>
  </div>

  <h2>The Opascope meeting — <em>3 questions.</em></h2>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">1. "What's our conversion action, and what changed in May 2025 when cost-per-conversion jumped from ~$40 to ~$600?"</p>
    <p class="ctx">Good: a clear answer (tracking change + what + when). Red flag: doesn't know, or can't explain the cliff.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">2. "We spend ~$3,200/mo on Google and pay you [confirm fee]. How do you justify the fee vs. managed media — and what's the path to more media or a lower fee?"</p>
    <p class="ctx">Good: acknowledges the inversion + a real plan. Red flag: defends the retainer without addressing the ratio.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="card qa">
    <p class="q">3. "Why are we 100% on broad membership terms while software terms starve and consumer-insurance queries leak budget — where's the awareness-stage + negative-keyword strategy?"</p>
    <p class="ctx">Good: a real keyword/awareness framework + negative list. Red flag: "that's just how dental search works." It isn't.</p>
  </div>
  <p style="font-size:0.9rem;color:var(--ink-soft)">Plus: <strong>Who owns the account?</strong> (if it's Opascope, you lose 15 months of history on exit — get it transferred to a Clerri-owned account regardless of the decision.)</p>

  <div class="note-block">
    <div class="note-label">Paid search notes <span class="note-saved">✓ saved</span></div>
    <textarea data-note="paid-search-notes" placeholder="Opascope's answers, the conversion-action truth, the actual fee, account ownership, fix-vs-own decision..."></textarea>
  </div>

  <div class="topic-foot">
    <a href="/clerri/ad-strategy"><span class="dir">← Prev</span><span class="name">Ad Creative & Targeting</span></a>
    <a href="/clerri/vendor-audit"><span class="dir">Next →</span><span class="name">Vendor Audit</span></a>
  </div>

</div>

<style>
  .ptable { width:100%; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:0.86rem; margin:0.5rem 0 1rem; }
  .ptable th, .ptable td { text-align:left; padding:0.55rem 0.7rem; border-bottom:1px solid var(--cotton-dark); vertical-align:top; }
  .ptable th { font-family:'JetBrains Mono', monospace; font-size:0.66rem; letter-spacing:0.06em; text-transform:uppercase; color:var(--clerri-green); }
  .rnum { font-family:'Fraunces', serif; font-size:1.7rem; font-weight:700; color:var(--clerri-green); line-height:1; }
  .rlbl { font-size:0.8rem; color:var(--ink-soft); margin-top:0.4rem; line-height:1.4; }
  .qa { margin-bottom:0.75rem; }
  .qa .q { font-weight:600; color:var(--ink); margin:0 0 0.4rem; font-size:0.95rem; }
  .qa .ctx { color:var(--muted); margin:0; font-size:0.875rem; font-style:italic; }
  h4 .pill, .card .pill { font-size:0.6rem; }
</style>

</ClerriLayout>
